---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { internalHref, siteMeta } from "@/lib/site";
---

<BaseLayout title="kernc Reference" description="User-facing reference for kernc: driver modes, runtime flags, LLVM emission, direct linking, and freestanding build commands.">
  <section class="manual-page mx-auto px-5 pb-20 pt-14 md:px-8 md:pt-18">
    <div class="eyebrow">Compiler Driver</div>
    <h1 class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-5xl leading-[0.95] text-[color:var(--kern-ink)] md:text-6xl">
      `kernc`
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
      `kernc` is the compiler and linker driver. It parses, checks, lowers,
      emits LLVM or native linker inputs, and can invoke the final system
      linker. It does not resolve packages or own lockfiles.
    </p>

    <div class="manual-callout mt-10">
      <div class="manual-kicker">Validated Surface</div>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-base">
        <li>The direct commands on this page were exercised while writing the site docs.</li>
        <li>Hosted compile-and-link, compile-only plus `--link-only`, and `--emit-llvm` all work as documented.</li>
        <li>Freestanding direct linking works with `--runtime-entry none`, `--entry-symbol _start`, and explicit linker args.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Driver modes</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`kernc src/main.rn -o app
kernc -c src/main.rn -o app.o
kernc --emit-llvm src/main.rn
kernc --link-only --link-input app.o -o app`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>Default mode compiles the source input and links the final binary.</li>
        <li>`-c` emits a linker input artifact and stops before the final system link.</li>
        <li>`--emit-llvm[=raw|verified|optimized]` prints LLVM IR to stdout instead of linking.</li>
        <li>`--link-only` skips the frontend and code generation and invokes the linker with explicit inputs.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Core flags</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`--runtime-entry none|rt|crt
--runtime-libc yes|no
--library-bundle none|base|std
--entry-symbol _start
--module-path std=./library/std
--metadata-output out/meta
--target x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu
--link-input file.o
--link-search native
--link-lib demo
--link-arg ARG
--print-link-command
--timings`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>`--runtime-entry` controls startup ownership.</li>
        <li>`--runtime-libc` controls whether libc is linked.</li>
        <li>`--library-bundle` wires the official library roots such as `base` or `std`.</li>
        <li>`--entry-symbol` overrides the symbol used as the final linker entry.</li>
        <li>`--module-path` and `--module-interface-path` are the explicit module-root hooks for direct-driver use.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Hosted user program</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`kernc \
  --runtime-entry rt \
  --runtime-libc no \
  --library-bundle std \
  src/main.rn \
  -o app`}</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        This is the normal direct-driver shape for one source file that wants
        the hosted `rt` startup path and the `std` library bundle.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Split compile and link</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`kernc -c \
  --runtime-entry rt \
  --runtime-libc no \
  --library-bundle std \
  src/main.rn \
  -o app.o

kernc --link-only \
  --runtime-entry rt \
  --runtime-libc no \
  --library-bundle std \
  --link-input app.o \
  -o app`}</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        Use this when another tool needs to stage, inspect, cache, or post-process
        the linker input before the final link step.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Inspect LLVM IR</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`kernc --emit-llvm \
  --runtime-entry rt \
  --runtime-libc no \
  --library-bundle std \
  src/main.rn > app.ll`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>Use `raw`, `verified`, or `optimized` when you need a specific pipeline stage.</li>
        <li>The emitted IR still reflects the explicit runtime and library flags you selected.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Freestanding direct build</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`#[export_name("_start")]
fn kmain() void {
    for (;;) {}
    @unreachable();
}`}</code></pre>
      <pre class="doc-code mt-6"><code>{`kernc \
  --runtime-entry none \
  --runtime-libc no \
  --library-bundle base \
  --entry-symbol _start \
  src/main.rn \
  -o kernel.bin`}</code></pre>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>`--runtime-entry none` means `kernc` does not require a program `main`.</li>
        <li>`--library-bundle base` keeps the library surface freestanding-oriented.</li>
        <li>`--entry-symbol _start` tells the final link which symbol should be treated as the entry.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Freestanding with a linker script</h2>
      <pre class="doc-code"><code>{`kernc \
  --runtime-entry none \
  --runtime-libc no \
  --library-bundle base \
  --entry-symbol _start \
  --link-arg -T \
  --link-arg /absolute/path/to/kernel.ld \
  src/main.rn \
  -o kernel.bin`}</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-[color:var(--kern-text-muted)]">
        `kernc` passes raw linker arguments through exactly as requested. When
        you are inside a package project, prefer `craft` plus
        `b.link_script("kernel.ld")` so the package root path is resolved
        correctly for you.
      </p>
      <div class="manual-links mt-6">
        <a class="button-primary" href={internalHref("/guide/freestanding-and-linking/")}>
          Freestanding guide
        </a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={internalHref("/reference/craft")}>
          `craft` reference
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>When to use `kernc` directly</h2>
      <ul class="mt-5 space-y-3 text-base">
        <li>One explicit compile or link command in another build system.</li>
        <li>IR inspection with `--emit-llvm`.</li>
        <li>Freestanding bring-up before a package layout exists.</li>
        <li>Explicit linker experimentation where you want full control over each argument.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="manual-section">
      <h2>Maintainer deep dive</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-base">
        If you are changing the compiler driver itself, the repository keeps
        lower-level `kernc` integration details and implementation notes.
      </p>
      <div class="manual-links mt-6">
        <a class="button-primary" href={`${siteMeta.repoUrl}/blob/main/docs/kernc.md`} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
          Open maintainer doc
        </a>
        <a class="button-secondary" href={internalHref("/reference")}>
          Back to reference tracks
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
